gdom","Scole, Depwade, Norfolk, England":"Scole, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom",", Shelton, Norfolk, England":"Shelton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Shelton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Shelton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Westwick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Westwick (Durham, Essex, Norfolk, WR Yorks)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Shelton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire): habitational name primarily from Shelton (Nottinghamshire), but also from Shelton (Bedfordshire, Norfolk, Shropshire, and Staffordshire). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Isabell Westwick de Shelton was born in 1213, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Serionis Westwick and Mrs Serionis Westwick. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Sir Henry De Shelton 7th Lord of Shelton, Knight. She died in 1284, in her hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1213–1284":"1213–1284","1211–1271":"1211–1271","1230–1257":"1230–1257","1256–1303":"1256–1303","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1262–1304":"1262–1304","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","before 1213":"enne 1213","ABT 1257":"umbes 1257","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1284":"1284","1185":"1185","21 February 1271":"21. veebruar 1271","1260"